"ogimage":"http://s3-media3.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/FC3kU7PKD68yn1-g3CLmxg/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.0",
"reviewcomment":"I managed to try Currywurst on my first night in Berlin, at a real, sit-down restaurant. But the dish initially was sold from small street stands and became popular with construction workers after the war, and I wanted to try Currywurst from one of these stands. At our hotel, we were told the most iconic Currywurst places in Berlin are Curry 36 in the west and Konnopke&#39;s Imbiss in the east.<br><br>We got our Currywurst with casing, and just the curry ketchup on the fries, no mayonnaise. It&#39;s fast food, so the order is ready very quickly and is relatively inexpensive. There&#39;s no seating near the stand, you just eat quickly, standing up at one of the high tables, and then go about your way.<br><br>As far as taste, I think it was delicious. The fries took me back decades to my childhood. Germans use different potatoes than we do in America, and I hadn&#39;t tasted fries like that since I was a kid and lived in Germany.",
