"categorystrlist":"Wine Bars,         German,         Coffee & Tea",
"ogimage":"http://s3-media2.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Ks6IyppcTEczkDGgVULCFA/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Who says Germans don&#39;t have good wine?  Weinstein says and proves this wrong.<br><br>Cute, homey interior that screams neighborhood joint.  Our server spoke perfect English and provided us with an English menu (which was not expected, but much appreciated).  He even helped us with our awful German pronunciations.  The reason to come here is the wine and wine parings.  You can really tell that they spent a lot of time honing a wine list and coming up with food to compliment each selection.  Each menu item was listed with a recommended wine; many of which were of German origin.  We went with each of the suggestions and came away impressed.<br><br>What we had (see pictures for visuals):<br>- Fried bread with pesto sauce:  Thin slices of bread that seemed to be sauteed in butter.  No need to tell you how good this was<br>- Winter vegetable salad:  Super fresh greens and dressed perfectly<br>- Cheese spatzle: The best we had in Berlin.  Crispy, cheesy, and savory<br>- Duck with brussels sprouts and fried stuffing:  Finely done duck.  A touch past where I normally want it cooked, but still medium rare.  The sprouts were great, but the fried stuffing thingy stole the show.  No clue what it actually was, but it reminded me of thanksgiving style stuffing fried in duck fat.  Awesome!<br>-Caramel ice cream:  German&#39;s oddly love ice cream (something cold on a freezing day?) and this was tasty example of why.  Rich and seemed homemade.<br><br>I can&#39;t recommend this place enough.  My wife and I really felt at home at Weinstein and would go back in a heartbeat.",
